{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"2783e963-4177-4672-b9af-8e961b9fcbea","content":"These are three distinct C# 15 breaking changes. Here's what's happening in each case:\n\n---\n\n**1. `SpanHelper.cs` — Stricter `scoped` ref lifetime enforcement**\n\nC# 15 tightens ref safety: assigning a loop-body-scoped `Span<int>` (`items`) to an outer-scoped `scoped Span<int>` (`results`) is now a compile error. The inner span's storage doesn't survive the loop iteration, so `results` would dangle. C# 14 didn't catch this.\n\n**Fix:** Use a `List<int>` instead of trying to widen a span's lifetime across scopes:\n\n```csharp\npublic static int[] ProcessItems(int[] source)\n{\n    var results = new List<int>();\n    foreach (var x in source)\n    {\n        results.Add(x * 2);\n    }\n    return results.ToArray();\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n**2. `Metadata.cs` — `nameof(this.X)` no longer allowed in attributes**\n\nC# 14 let `nameof` reference instance members in attribute arguments (since it's compile-time only). C# 15 tightens this: `this` is not permitted in attribute contexts. The bare member name still works.\n\n**Fix:** Drop the `this.` qualifier:\n\n```csharp\n[System.Obsolete(nameof(Endpoint))]\nvoid LegacyConnect() { }\n```\n\n---\n\n**3. `Pipeline.cs` — `with` keyword ambiguity in collection expressions**\n\nC# 15 expands the syntactic role of `with`, making `with(x, y)` inside a collection expression `[...]` ambiguous to the parser. It no longer resolves as a method call.\n\n**Fix:** Escape the identifier with `@`:\n\n```csharp\nobject @with(object a, object b) => (a, b);\nobject[] items = [@with(x, y), z];\n```\n\nOr simply rename the method to avoid clashing with the keyword (e.g., `Combine`).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c6d272d5-2957-49df-ac6c-e3d30a2074df","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about C# 15 / .NET 11 breaking changes. These are future versions (as of my knowledge cutoff), so let me reason about what I know and what migh